<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1735,2013]" pageId="6" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,368,1878,1904]" pageId="6" pageNumber="584">Identification.</emphasis>
This species was identified using the descriptions and illustrations by 
<bibRefCitation author="Flint, O. S., Jr." box="[1195,1336,1879,1905]" pageId="6" pageNumber="584" pagination="1 - 113" refId="ref5687" refString="Flint, O. S., Jr. (1991) Studies of Neotropical caddisflies, XLV: The taxonomy, phenology, and faunistics of the Trichoptera of Antioquia, Colombia. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 520, 1 - 113. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.520" type="journal article" year="1991">Flint (1991)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmid, F." pageId="6" pageNumber="584" pagination="1 - 126" refId="ref6761" refString="Schmid, F. (1982) La famille des Xiphocentronides (Trichoptera: Annulipalpia). Memoires de la Societe Entomologique du Canada, 121, 1 - 126. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 114122 fv" type="journal article" year="1982">Schmid (1982)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Vilarino, A. &amp; Santos Dias, E. &amp; Bispo, P. C." box="[284,520,1915,1941]" pageId="6" pageNumber="584" refId="ref7127" refString="Vilarino, A., Santos Dias, E. &amp; Bispo, P. C. (2021) Phylogeny indicates polyphyly in Cnodocentron (Trichoptera: Xiphocentronidae): biogeography and revision of New World species (Caenocentron). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, zlab 077. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / zoolinnean / zlab 077" type="book" year="2021">
Vilarino 
<emphasis box="[382,430,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="584">et al</emphasis>
. (2021)
</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1991" box="[529,845,1915,1941]" class="Insecta" family="Xiphocentronidae" genus="Caenocentron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="immaculatum">
<emphasis box="[529,845,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="584">Caenocentron immaculatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmid 1982" authorityName="Schmid" authorityYear="1982" box="[1047,1318,1915,1941]" class="Insecta" family="Xiphocentronidae" genus="Caenocentron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galesus">
<emphasis box="[1047,1162,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="584">C. galesus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Schmid, F." box="[1168,1318,1915,1941]" pageId="6" pageNumber="584" pagination="1 - 126" refId="ref6761" refString="Schmid, F. (1982) La famille des Xiphocentronides (Trichoptera: Annulipalpia). Memoires de la Societe Entomologique du Canada, 121, 1 - 126. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 114122 fv" type="journal article" year="1982">Schmid 1982</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the apical segment of each inferior appendage in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1991" box="[692,876,1951,1977]" class="Insecta" family="Xiphocentronidae" genus="Caenocentron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="immaculatum">
<emphasis box="[692,876,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="584">C. immaculatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is broader and more strongly arched, and the basal segment bears a strong tooth near the ventral margin.
</paragraph>
